{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491075"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"825"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/825"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.18,0.6,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/825"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96947"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of chest pain, a dry cough, haemoptysis and some difficulty breathing. Five days ago he underwent surgery for a fractured neck of femur. Until this morning he was making a steady recovery. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/86 mmHg, SpO2 86% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Examination of his chest shows reduced breath sounds at the left lung base but is otherwise clear. An arterial blood gas show respiratory alkalosis. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sputum cultures","Empirical antibiotics","Admit for monitoring","CT pulmonary angiogram","Thoracentesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst it is most likely that this patient\u0027s current problem is infective in origin, a pulmonary embolus must be considered and if thought a real possibility, the diagnosis must be excluded. This patient has a moderate - high pre-test probability of pulmonary embolism given his recent surgical history, his tachycardia and hypoxia. His Well\u0027s score is at least 4 (tachycardia, haemoptysis and recent surgery with immobilisation) but can be increased to 7 if includes the criteria of pulmonary embolism is #1 or equally likely diagnosis). A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E (CTPA) to exclude pulmonary embolism is reasonable given significant hypoxia and high pre-test probability. This investigation can be done in the outpatient or Emergency Department setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA D-dimer is less useful in this case due to the high pre-test probability of pulmonary embolism and the fact the D-dimer may be elevated post-surgically. The other differential is infection and there is some evidence of left basal consolidation with a small effusion on chest X-ray but pulmonary embolism should be excluded due to high pre-test probability and significant consequences if pulmonary embolism is undiagnosed and untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the CT pulmonary angiogram is clear, the focus should be on the likely chest infection. He may well need to be \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmitted\u003C/strong\u003E to hospital, \u003Cstrong\u003Esputum cultures\u003C/strong\u003E performed and started on antibiotics. At this stage the effusion is very small and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The CTPA should be used appropriately and indication for its use based on the patient\u0027s Well\u0027s score."],"references":["Maughan BC, Jarman AF, Redmond A, et al. Pulmonary embolism. BMJ 2024; 384;e071662"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96947"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"825"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15500"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15500"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/74080cd5-81ab-4a15-838e-e1edf3dab657.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/74080cd5-81ab-4a15-838e-e1edf3dab657.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":558,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96947"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T14:41:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T14:41:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"825"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114941"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headin